<TITLE> Mexico returns to competition after swine flu row </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NASSAU, June 3 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Mexico will return teams to South American competitions, ending their brief self-imposed exile after a row concerning swine flu. Nicolas Leoz, president of the South American Football Confederation (CFS), told reporters that a meeting between the Mexican Football Federation (FMF) and his body had ended the dispute. "The Mexican teams are back in the competitions. I am very happy that everything is resolved," said Leoz. Justin Compean, president of the FMF, said that as well as the clubs returning to the Copa Libertadores next season, Mexico would compete in the Copa America for national teams in 2011 in Argentina as originally planned. The deal was struck at a meeting before the FIFA congress which is due to open later on Tuesday. Mexico, part of the CONCACAF confederation for North and Central America and the Caribbean, features in South American competition as a guest team. The Mexicans pulled out of all events on May 8 in protest at the refusal of two South American teams to play in Mexico due to fears over swine 
